{
  "doc_id": "47357",
  "text": "There are several animal models of NAFLD, each with advantages and disadvantages [CITATION_1] . Here, we adopted a commonly used nutritional model, which utilises a high-fat and high-cholesterol diet to induce fatty liver disease. Using this model, our animals developed visceral obesity and hyperlipidaemia after 4 weeks with high-fat feeding, in addition to hepatic steatosis as detected by liver histology. At the end of 12 weeks, the rats showed an abnormal hepatic enzyme spectrum, and histological analysis revealed the presence of hepatitis. All of the above data indicate that we were able to use a HFD to create a NASH model that reflects the major features of human NAFLD.",
